fullName: Mortality rate attributed to unintentional poisoning
dataDefinition: Mortality rate attributed to unintentional poisonings is the number of deaths from unninstentional poisonings in a year per 100,000 population.  Unintentional poisonings can be caused by household chemicals, pesticides, kerosene, carbon monoxide and medicines, or can be the result of environmental contamination or occupational chemical exposure.
dataProcessingMethod: Retrieved from World Bank World Development Indicators Website on October 14, 2020.
dataCollectionMethod: Compiled by the World Health Organization, the data in this dataset come from official death registration data where available (see notes).
Source_1: World Develpment Indicators, The World Bank
Source_2: World Health Organization, Global Health Observatory Data Repository (apps.who.int/ghodata/)
